(110, 43, 9, 'This comes from a report about a question asking \\"How many seconds (minimum) must be on the period clock at the end of a jam for a new jam to start [...]\\"\r\n\r\nThe rule: 2.3.4 - If 30 seconds or fewer remain on the period clock when a jam ends, there will not be another jam started [...]\r\n\r\nThe question: assuming your period clock only has seconds, this is fine, but what if you have an ace NSO who uses the lap-timer feature to get the exact time the four whistles end. What if they look down and see a time of 30.5? Is the cut off for \\"30 seconds or fewer\\" 30.00, or 30.99, or you you round? \r\n\r\nI\\\'d be inclined to think the cut off is 30.00, but if so why isn\\\'t it simply worded \\"fewer than 30 seconds\\"?\r\n\r\nLikly to happen? No. Pedantic? Very. ', 1370029297, 3, 0),
(111, 43, 9, 'It is worded that way because the rules were written by Americans. (there\\\'s a joke to be made there about English being their second language)\r\n\r\nRealistically, though, it has to be \\\'30 or less\\\' because the time between jams is supposed to be exactly 30 seconds. At 30.00 seconds there isn\\\'t enough time to start a new jam. At 30.01 there is. In theory. ', 1370031834, 3455, 0),
(112, 37, 3, 'Pictures, or even better gifs, would be a great help to people. \r\n\r\nIt\\\'s quite frustrating that WFTDA refuses to do any kind of animated image of the signals. What with them being arm motions, rather than static poses and all. \r\n\r\nAside from that, a glossary section would be nice as well. ', 1370032089, 3455, 0),
(113, 43, 9, 'I agree there, but by that interpretation if the clock reads 30, we go again. Which, seems counter-intuitive to the rule.', 1370040893, 3, 0),
(114, 41, 3, 'And suggestions are more than welcome :) I don\\\'t tend to chat about what I\\\'ve got planned as it changes so much. It\\\'s nice for me when people suggest stuff I\\\'ve thought about myself, it\\\'s quite affirming.', 1370041065, 3, 0),
(115, 44, 6, 'Rules say refs dont need to warn skaters before issuing a warning (official rules test agees). But, \\"Failure to Return\\" penalty can only be issued once an Out of Play warning has been issued. What is going on?\r\n\r\nSimply, the \\"Out of Play\\" warning is NOT a warning that the skater is about to get a FTR penalty. It just happens to come before you get an FTR penalty.\r\n\r\nIf a penalty did have to be issued, you\\\'d hear \\"out of play!\\" \\"Failure to reform\\" \\"whistle (colour) (number) Failure to reform Major\\".', 1370077215, 3, 1370125662),
