(66, '71.23.91.114', 1335444933, 344, 0, 'Question #344: I\\\'m reporting question #93 because ... \r\n\r\nFirst there’s:\r\n\r\n2.6.4.1 If the officials call a time out during a jam in progress, the jam will end and a new jam will be run if there is time remaining on the official period clock (see Section 2.3.4).\r\n\r\nThere’s a distinct difference between “officials” and “referees” in the rules, thus the inclusion of “officials” in this rule allows for the possibility of a non-skating official to call a timeout. And also:\r\n\r\n2.8.2.3 Officials must stop the official period clock between jams when time exceeds thirty (30) seconds.\r\n\r\nThe official period clock is stopped only for timeouts (2.8.2.2), thus the officials can only stop the clock by calling an official timeout. \r\n\r\nBasically, non-skating officials may call timeouts, however they may only be official timeouts. Only referees may signal for a team timeout; they don’t actually call the timeout, the Captain or Designated Alternate from either team does. \r\n\r\nRDRotD', 3),
