(771, '68.113.165.220', 1390243840, 1515, 0, 'Question #1515: I\\\'m reporting question #1515 because ... \r\nWFTDA Rules Publication\r\nPASSING WHILE AIRBORNE - UPDATED 6/26/13\r\n\r\nJanuary 17, 2013\r\n\r\nQ:\r\nIn order to score points while airborne, does a Jammer need to \\"stick\\" the landing?\r\n\r\nA:\r\nIn order to score points while airborne, the Jammer must establish contact feet-first and in-bounds at the moment of landing. A Jammer satisfies this requirement if any part of their foot or skate is the first point of contact upon landing, with no part of their body touching out of bounds at the point of initial contact with the track. Thus, if any part of the Jammer’s foot/skate has touched in-bounds at the moment of initial contact upon landing, the Jammer has immediately satisfied this requirement. Anything that happens after this point (falling, stepping out of bounds, etc.) is irrelevant to scoring, but will be taken into account for other rules purposes (such as cutting the track, low blocking, etc).\r\n\r\nExample:\r\nJammer is completely in-bounds and ceases contact with the track as part of an apex jump. The first part of the Jammer’s body to contact the floor is their right foot, which makes contact in-bounds. The Jammer’s left foot then lands out of bounds. This Jammer will be eligible to receive points for all opposing skaters passed while airborne, but will also be eligible for a cut track should they re-enter play in front of opposing skaters passed while airborne.', 2),
(772, '143.235.186.74', 1392835775, 1332, 0, 'Question #1332: I\\\'m reporting question #1332 because ... \r\n\r\nIt\\\'s not clear without the context of being in the OOB section that the question is asking about a penalty on the skater being forced out rather than on the skater forcing them out.\r\n\r\nThere isn\\\'t enough information to know if the skater initiating the block did so legally, but with only answers that assume the block was illegal, it can be read to be talking about assigning a penalty to a skater who blocks another skater out of bounds with an illegal block.', 3),
